<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Submission to the Department of Culture Media and Sport</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Mr. C. D. Lee-Koo [FBB0049]</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">DCMS Inquiry: “Future of the BBC”</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 63.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 63.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">“There is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal"> no worse tyranny than to force a man to pay for what he does not want merely because you t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">hink it would be good for him.”</span><a name="_ednref1"></a><a href="#_edn1">[i]</a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">This submission is in response to the following questions posed by this inquiry:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">How should the BBC be funded beyond 2016?</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">How shou</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ld the BBC be governed, regulated and held accountable beyond 2016?</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Executive Summary</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 16.65pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The BBC’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">TV</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Licence fee tax </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and the criminal prosecution regime used to enforce it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">abolished</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in its entirety</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 16.65pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The BBC should be privatised permitting it to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">obtain </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">funding by voluntary subscription and commercial advertising. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 16.65pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The BBC should be regulated by Ofcom on equal footing with other broadcasters.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Why the BBC’s TV Lice</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">nce fee tax should be abolished</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 16.65pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In effect</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the BBC has the legal right to threaten </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UK households with criminal prosecution for non-payment of its services.  </span></li></ol><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 16.65pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The BBC has the ultimate power </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> obtain a search warrant to search an occupier’s home for TV equipment and other evidence of watching live TV. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 16.65pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">These are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disgraceful</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> powers for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tate broadcaster to have and are incompatible with any notion of a free society. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For these reasons alone, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BBC’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">TV Licence fee tax regime should be abolished</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in its entirety</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Misconceptions about the BBC TV Licence fee tax</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 16.65pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are many </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">misconceptions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> which surround the BBC’s TV Licence fee</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> many of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> which the BBC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">continue</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> perp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">etuate either deliberately or implicitly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Misconception: ‘The TV Licensing authority is not the BBC’</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 16.65pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A misconception which still persists to this day, which conti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nues to be perpetuated by the BBC, is that it is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">somehow</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> disconnected from the collection of the TV Tax and that a separate authority is responsible for collecting TV Tax revenue. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 16.65pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In its own journalism, the BBC refers to the “TV Licensing authority” as if</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> it was a separate body</span><a name="_ednref2"></a><a href="#_edn2">[ii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> where in fact it is the BBC itself. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The BBC is the TV Licensing authority under section 364 of the Communications Act 2003</span><a name="_ednref3"></a><a href="#_edn3">[iii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 16.65pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The BBC is the owner of a registered trad</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e mark “TV Licensing™”</span><a name="_ednref4"></a><a href="#_edn4">[iv]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> under the banner of which it presents i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tself to the public as the licensing authority.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Inspection</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of communication from “TV Licensing™” </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reveals no overt statement that the BBC is in fact the licensing authority.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 16.65pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The BBC licences external contractors to use this registered trade mark </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">“TV Licens</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing™” </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to collect the Licence fee revenue on its behalf.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 16.65pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The obfuscation surrounding the ‘TV Licensing authority’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> perpetuated by the BBC in its own journalism, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is plainly intended to shield the BBC brand name from the unsavoury business of collecting the T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">V Licence fee tax and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the prosecution of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> householders for non-payment.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For the purposes of this submission, where applicable, I shall refer to the BBC’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">TV Licensing™</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> trade mark and its authorised contract agents simply as the “BBC”.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Misconception: ‘The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">TV Licence fee is a payment for BBC services’</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A tax is defined as a “compulsory contribution to state revenue”</span><a name="_ednref5"></a><a href="#_edn5">[v]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In 2006, the Office of National Statistics reclassified the TV Licence fee as a tax</span><a name="_ednref6"></a><a href="#_edn6">[vi]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This officially </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sanctioned the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> end to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the erroneous,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ut widely held view</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that the TV Licence fee wa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s a ‘service payment’ for BBC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The recognition that the payment is in fact a tax and not a ‘payment for services’ was an important step forward to recognise the unique position of t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he BBC in regard to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> its funding:  p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ayment for the BBC via the TV Licence fee is a tax backed by the full force of state criminal prosecution powers.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Although increasingly less prevalent, some members of the public still continue to believe the TV Licence is a payment for BBC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> services and not a tax. This is not helped by statements of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">senior </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BBC management who continue to perpetuate the myth that the TV Licence fee is a voluntary payment.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In a speech by</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Lord Hall,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the current Director General of the BBC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the following statemen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t was made: </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">"The people of this country make a bold and generous commitment in paying for the BBC. They own it, they love it, and they expect only the best from it."</span><a name="_ednref7"></a><a href="#_edn7">[vii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This statement made by Lord Hall is at odds with the compulsory aspect of the BBC TV Li</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cence fee.  UK households do not make a “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bold and generous commitment in paying for the BBC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”.  ‘Generosity’ implies the payments are somehow made voluntarily. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In fact the British public are compelled to pay for the BBC (whether they watch it or not) or fa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ce the full force of criminal prosecution.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Misconception: “If you have a TV </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">or watch TV </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">you must pay the TV Licence”</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Routine BBC TV Licensing ‘threat’ letters contain misleading titles and intimidating wording carefully constructed to scare the occupier </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">into buying a BBC TV Licence.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The ominous and threatening content of these letters are disgraceful</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and incompatible with any notion of a free society</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  In most cases, t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he ‘threat’ letters </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are sent monthly to addresses for which the BBC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lists</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as unlicensed.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">They contain phrases like “W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hat to expect at court” even before it has been established whether the occupier needs a licence or not.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As recently as October 2013, the BBC sent a letter to unlicensed addresses with the following title:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 120.5pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">WHATEVER</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">YOU</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">RE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">WAT</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">CHING</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">, </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">HOWEVER</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">YOU’RE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">WATCHING</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">IT</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">, </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">YOUR</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">HOME</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">NEEDS</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> TV </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">LICENCE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">”</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This ‘threat’ letter title illegitimately perpetuates the myth that merely watching any TV requires a TV Licence.  The title taken on its own is blatantly false.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A BBC TV Licence is only needed if the occupier watches live </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">TV.  Just watching catch-up TV (becoming more prevalent) does not require a TV Licence.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The legal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, non-licensable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> catch-up only exception is not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">subsequently </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">made clear in the letter</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is pla</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">inly not in the BBC’s financial interest to do so. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Misconception: “Our TV Detector can detect if you are watching live TV”</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">All Freedom of Information requests (FOI) having </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">simple </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">technical questions about the operation of the BBC ‘TV Detector’ are routi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nely refused by the BBC</span><a name="_Ref372828454"></a><a name="_ednref8"></a><a href="#_edn8">[viii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the era of modern flat screen digital TV’s, the plethora of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">internet enabled </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mobile devices, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">so-called </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘TV detector’ is a technical absurdity. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In a surprising FOI request, the BBC admitted that TV Detector evidence has ne</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ver been used in a single prosecution</span><a name="_ednref9"></a><a href="#_edn9">[ix]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The BBC disclosed that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is only used to obtain search warrants</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The basis on which the warrants are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">obtained </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">appear exceptionally</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> dubious </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">both </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">technical</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">legally.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The operation of the ‘TV detector’ is most likel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y a device to detect any kind of screen based light emissions which results in a positive detection.  In a sworn oath applying for a search warrant, a positive detection was said to indicate a ‘97% confidence factor of a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">possible</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> broadcast’</span><a name="_ednref10"></a><a href="#_edn10">[x]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  Note the use</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of the word “possible” rather than actual. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Anyone can be 100% certain of a possible </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">anything. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is inferred that the BBC merely relies on the BARB statistic that 97% of UK homes have a TV</span><a name="_ednref11"></a><a href="#_edn11">[xi]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">At best this is utter nonsense and at worst the statement is downright misleading. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The result would inevitably mean justices of the peace and magistrates will issue search warrants against innocent citizens</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in some cases</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the days of the local oscillat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">or, the ‘TV Detector’ may have actually worked. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However the real use of the ‘TV Detector’ today is nothing more than an absurd scare tactic to get people to buy the BBC’s TV licences. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I am frankly ashamed and embarrassed that my country </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">continues to have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> this ridiculous anachronism to enforce payment for the state broadcaster.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The hidden cost of prosecutions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> and inherent unfairness of the enforcement process</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The BBC is effectively using the Magistrates Court system as an extension of its revenue raising o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">perations, the cost of which is again borne by the taxpayer.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It has been reported by the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BBC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> itself that in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2012, as many as 181,880 prosecutions were commenced by the BBC for non-payment of the BBC’s TV Licence fee</span><a name="_ednref12"></a><a href="#_edn12">[xii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This is said to be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">ten percent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of al</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l criminal prosecutions in the UK amounting to nearly 3500 every week.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">According to the BBC’s own article, a staggering 15% or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">26,745</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> cases were ‘unsuccessful</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><a name="_ednref13"></a><a href="#_edn13">[xiii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The ‘unsuccessful’ cases represent an astonishing number of people who have had their time was</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ted.  It raises the inference that the BBC commences prosecutions in the hope that people plead guilty and buy a TV Licence. If this were provable it would certainly be considered by any court to be an abuse of process.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Most disturbingly, the TV Licence pr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">osecutorial regime unfairly targets women. Two-thirds of those prosecuted by the BBC are women because they are most likely to be at home when the BBC’s TV Licensing enforcement contractors visit.</span><a name="_ednref14"></a><a href="#_edn14">[xiv]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The Moral Case for abolition</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> of the BBC TV Licence tax</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Fre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">edom and choice </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> fundamental in a democracy. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The TV Tax requires people to pay for the BBC irrespective of whether they consume any of its output or not.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Despite the fact that it has been frozen until 2016, £145.50 per year is a ridiculously large sum </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of money for a struggling, low income family to pay merely because they have a television which could otherwise be totally free to air.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The TV Licence is a shocking poll tax on the poor for no real reason other than to keep the state broadcaster on the ai</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The revenue the BBC gets from the licence fee ensures that it occupies a disproportionate space in the competition for audiences.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The BBC online presence is known to be squeezing local newspapers as it dominates the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">market</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by sheer weight of money.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> BBC TV Licence fee tax is a completely artificial added expense</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to UK households.  A TV is now a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> commodity household appliance. Televisions and other </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">internet enabled video </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">devices do not need the BBC to function. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A series of shocking scandals have destr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oyed the BBC’s moral claim to the TV Licence fee</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tax money for which it continues to receive as the sole beneficiary.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Evidence in the public domain </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">suggests</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that senior BBC executives knew about the vile conduct of Jimmy Savile and chose to do not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hing. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Questions remain</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as to what senior BB</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C staff knew about  an ongoing Newsnight investigation into Savile </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">when Christmas tributes to the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ir</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">now </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disgraced</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> former star were due to be aired</span><a name="_ednref15"></a><a href="#_edn15">[xv]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The libelling of Lord McAlpine</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with the most serious allegation that can be levelled at a private individual was scandalous and disgraceful.  There was a complete failure to perform the most obvious check which would have been to positively identify the individual at the centre of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">allegation.  This failure came at a staggering cost to the licence fee taxpayer for the libel amounting to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> £305,000 including legal costs</span><a name="_ednref16"></a><a href="#_edn16">[xvi]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The failed “Digital Media Initiative” DMI project was a flagrant waste of nearly £100 million of Licence fee payers’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> money.  Digital media archiving is something which all commercial TV operators undertake in some shape or form. The truth of the DMI waste scandal is yet to be adequately </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">explained to the British public</span><a name="_ednref17"></a><a href="#_edn17">[xvii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Massive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">overly generous </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BBC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pensions and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">salaries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">huge</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> contractual payments and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">extra-contractual </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">payoffs for ex-BBC staff have persisted </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and continue to persist </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in the news.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I submit this </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ll a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> direct consequence of an organisation with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a guaranteed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> income of £3.6 billion a year that is not subject </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">any </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">commercial pressure.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The continued rise of the internet and virtually limitless choice of on-demand services makes the compulsory charge of £145.50 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a year </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to fund the BBC merely </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">watching </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">occasional live TV</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a completely unjustifiable and unneces</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sary expense</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">At one point in the distant past, a television was a major piece of technology requiring an expensive infrastructure to support its operation. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Today</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> television is a commodity item like </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">any </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">other </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ordinary household item</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Technology is supplanting the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">television as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the main source of news and entertainment.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Smart-phones and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> other </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">portable </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">devices </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have video </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">capability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">both live and on-demand</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">continue </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">level a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tax on this particular </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">narrow range of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">household item</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> because they are used for ‘live’ broadcast viewing is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">absurd </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as it is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> obscene. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The BBC Trust model</span></p><ol start="45" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is ample evidence presented to both </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">parliamentary </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Public Accounts and Culture M</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">edia a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nd Sport Select C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ommittees that discloses</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a st</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">artling picture of the BBC Trust being in a position of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">apparent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oversight of the BBC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">without</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">any </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">authority </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">affect</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">day to day </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">decisions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BBC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">executive.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The BBC Trust model in which the BBC Trust acts as both the cheerleader and regulator of the BBC has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">spectacularly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">failed in the wake of the scandals.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Conclusion</span></p><ol start="47" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Citing the above, t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he BBC TV Licence fee is a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n unfair, unjust</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, compulsory</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> expense imposed on a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ll British households</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> which is completely unnecessary</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It should be abolished in its entirety.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Post 2016, the legacy BBC infrastructure should be privatised and turned into a voluntary subscription </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and advertising funding model</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">placing it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">commercial</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> footing like any other broadcaster.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As a privatised organisation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> freed from the subsidy of the taxpayer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the new BBC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> can then answer to its advertising and subscription base</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> subject to regulation by</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the government watchdog </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Ofcom</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in line with other broad</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">casters.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">End Notes</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn1"></a><a href="#_ednref1">[i]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">The Moon is a Harsh Mistress</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">”,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Robert A. Heinlein</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn2"></a><a href="#_ednref2">[ii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">UK still has 13,000 black-and-white TVs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">”, BBC Online, </span><a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-20957218"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-20957218</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn3"></a><a href="#_ednref3">[iii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2003/21/section/364"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2003/21/section/364</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn4"></a><a href="#_ednref4">[iv]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Intellectual P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">ropert